<p>My latest example of such migration is the case of <a href="/">this</a>, and my other <a href="http://breakthebeat.org">non-tech blog</a>. The blogs are hosted at Tumblr and Posterous, respectively.</p>

<p>I have always used a custom domain for them, but I started by having subdomains of my majx.org mapped, like <code>breakbit.majx.org</code> and <code>breakbeat.majx.org</code>. As my contribution to the blogs is rising, and some articles caught some popularity, I decided it was time to purchase the real thing. Since .COM’s were taken, I settled with the .ORG.</p>

<p>It’s a bit of a risky process, but it can be done without any major harm.</p>

<h2>Don’t do nothing</h2>

<p>The worst thing you can do is to do <em>nothing</em>. Nothing as in moving your content and living on. This breaks all of the links from other people to you, and breaks search results for your content. <strong>Do not do this!</strong></p>

<p>Better ways are providing a notice on the old domain, saying your site has moved and maybe throwing in a <code><meta refresh></code> that loads the new domain. Still, this doesn’t rescue much of your old internet fame.</p>

<p>The absolute best way is to send the HTTP 301 status, which stands for <strong>Moved permanently</strong>. Search engines honor this and replace their index with the new URLs whenever the encounter it.</p>

<p>So building from this knowledge, it would be perfect if we could capture all requests to the old domain and just redirect them with the domain changed and the status of 301.</p>

<p>In my example, when my server gets the request for:</p>

<p><code>breakbit.majx.org/post/582420521/more-power-saving-in-linux</code></p>

<p>it should return a 301 with the address:</p>

<p><code>breakthebit.org/post/582420521/more-power-saving-in-linux</code></p>

<h2>Apache’s mod_rewrite</h2>

<p>Okay, so how we get about doing this. I kept it simple and since I’m using <a href="http://httpd.apache.org/">Apache</a>, I just used it’s powerful <a href="http://httpd.apache.org/docs/2.0/mod/mod_rewrite.html">mod_rewrite</a> tool. mod_rewrite is a complex beast and capable of doing many things. But for this particular purpose it’s configuration is straightforward:</p>

<pre><code><VirtualHost *:80>
  ServerName breakbit.majx.org
  ServerAdmin miha@rebernik.info

  DocumentRoot /webroot/default
  <Directory /webroot/default>
    Options FollowSymLinks
    AllowOverride None
  </Directory>

  RewriteEngine On
  RewriteRule ^(.*)$ <a href="http://breakthebit.org">http://breakthebit.org</a>$1 [R=301,L]
</VirtualHost>
</code></pre>

<p>As you can see, you need to put this configuration inside the virtual host. Then just start the rewrite engine and put the rewriting rule in. The rule is simple and it’s regular expression <code>^(.*)$</code> just matches any URL under the breakbit.majx.org domain. The <code>$1</code> is the captured requested URL.</p>

<p>You can check it out in action right here, by clicking on this link, pointing to the <a href="http://breakbit.majx.org/post/564380600/pimp-my-linux-ubuntu-10-04">Pimp my Linux</a> article on the old domain. Notice the domain instantly changes to the new one. That’s 301 in action.</p>

<p>To use this for yourself, you can just replace the <code>ServerName</code> with your own <strong>old</strong> domain, and replace the <code>breakthebit.org</code> with the <strong>new</strong> domain that you want to redirect to.</p>

<p><code>R=301</code> forces the redirect to be a 301 Moved permanently.</p>

<p><code>L</code> means this rule is the last one, so if matched skip all those that follow.</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:37:"http://breakthebit.org/post/583792952";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:37:"http://breakthebit.org/post/583792952";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Sun, 09 May 2010 13:34:00 +0200";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:6:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"apache";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:11:"mod_rewrite";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"domain";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"migration";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:11:"redirection";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:5;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3:"301";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:11;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:1:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:26:"More power saving in Linux";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2473:"<p>
Okay, so we covered steps to optimize your Linux netbook in the previous <a href="http://breakbit.majx.org/post/564380600/pimp-my-linux-ubuntu-10-04">post</a>. Now let’s take a look at some further steps to squeeze the last watts out of those cells.
</p>

<p>
The trick is to get on board with <a href="http://samwel.tk/laptop_mode/">laptop-mode-tools</a>, which is a set of scripts that hooks into the ACPI daemon. This in turn executes the scripts when you plug or unplug your machine and makes certain optimisations accordingly.
</p>

<p>
Laptop mode is a kernel operating mode in which it takes great care not to spin the disk too much. This in turn makes it possible to keep the disk in the low-powered mode for a longer period of time.
</p>

<p>Let’s begin with the installation:</p>

<pre><code>$ sudo apt-get install laptop-mode-tools</code></pre>

<p>
The scripts will automatically be startedn on boot, so you can now proceed editing the configuration files. No GUI, sorry, this is done the Linux way.
</p>

<p>
Navigate to <code>/etc/laptop-mode</code> and open the file <code>laptop-mode.conf</code>. Navigate around the file a bit, to get a feeling of the thing. It’s well commented.
</p>

<p>
The thing we actually need to edit is down at the line <code>HD="/dev/[hs]d[abcdefgh]"</code>. This line sets which are our local hard-drives, that the scripts will control. The default value is a wildcard, but in our case, the netbook probably has only one disk. In my case this is the first SATA disk at <code>/dev/sda</code>. Change this to your primary disk(s).
</p>

<p>
Next step is to navigate into the <code>conf.d</code> directory and open each file as root and activate it by turning the 0 to 1. You can do this for most of the files, unless you see that the file controls some proprietary hardware that you <em>know you don’t have</em>. If unsure, leave it at 0, or better yet, Google it up.
</p>

<p>That’s it, you’re done. Now reboot and try out <code>powertop</code> to see how you improved your battery life.</p>

<p>In my testing on a Lenovo Ideapad S10-2, the battery time on idle went from 5h to 6,5 hours.</p>

<p>On the ASUS 1005PE I’m getting a solid 11 hours of battery life on light usage. This is of course courtesy of the more efficient Pine Trail chipset and Super Hybrid Engine.</p>

<p>More information can be found on the excellent <a href="http://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Laptop_Mode_Tools">Arch Linux wiki</a></p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:37:"http://breakthebit.org/post/582420521";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:37:"http://breakthebit.org/post/582420521";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Sun, 09 May 2010 01:05:00 +0200";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:6:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"powertop";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:11:"laptop-mode";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:17:"laptop-mode-tools";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:12:"power saving";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"ubuntu";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:5;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"linux";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:12;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:1:{s:0:"";a:5:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:20:"Google's new clothes";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1839:"<p>
Aye, Google did it. I was writing about this upcoming change of the basic <em>design of search</em> in my previous article <a href="http://breakbit.majx.org/post/423959710/googles-upcoming-ui">Google’s upcoming UI</a>.
</p>
<p>Well it’s here, and it’s being deployed across the board to users everywhere. As far as I can see, this includes all languages as well. Okay, not exactly all, the <a href="http://www.google.com/search?hl=ar&source=hp&q=%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%A9&lr=&aq=f&aqi=n1g10&aql=&oq=&gs_rfai=">Arabic</a> search results page stayed the same, probably because of the different orientation.</p>

<img src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_l22hhwNkxM1qahol6.png" alt="Google's new UI"/><p>This new look exposes more of Google to ordinary users, which may have never that there are things beyond Google’s page search and image search.</p>
<p>It’s nice to have this segmentation of results so handy, though they should integrate the “maps” view, to be more consistent. Right now it just throws you to the regular maps site.</p>
<p>This new design also shows the magnitude of Google’s reach, and how far it has spread during the years.</p>

<img src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_l22hzdXIdU1qahol6.png"/><p>
This is how searching the updates looks like. It’s supposed to be the next big thing in search, and it’s updated in real-time. Google <a href="http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2009/10/rt-google-tweets-and-updates-and-search.html">stroke a deal</a> with Twitter to make this happen (similar deal happened between Twitter and Bing, as Twitter wants to stay neutral and unbiased).
</p>
<p>As usual with Google, the layout could be a little more aligned, and there are a couple of inconsistencies.</p>
<p>All in all though, great job. This stuff makes better search possible faster.</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:37:"http://breakthebit.org/post/579539151";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:37:"http://breakthebit.org/post/579539151";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Fri, 07 May 2010 22:55:00 +0200";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:13;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:1:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:34:"Optimize Ubuntu 10.04 on a netbook";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:33950:"<p><a class="content" href="#contents">Skip to content ↓</a></p>

<div class="disclaimer">
<h2>Disclaimer</h2>
<p>
  This tutorial is targeted at netbook users, that want to streamline and tweak their Linux. Though it’s perfectly suitable for other 
  people, provided they have the necessary knowledge. It has been tested on and meant mainly for the new 
  <a href="http://www.ubuntu.com/getubuntu/download-netbook" title="Download Ubuntu Netbook Edition | Ubuntu">Ubuntu 10.04 release</a>
  on an ASUS eeePC 1005PE and a Lenovo S10-2, both running the <abbr title="Release Candidate">RC</abbr> version.
</p>
<p>
  Be careful with what you are doing, and you’ll be fine. Use information here at your own risk.
</p>
</div>

<h2>Overview</h2>

<p>
  So, I recently purchased a new netbook, the AmSUS eeePC 1005PE, which got me with it’s serious autonomy, rated to last 
  around 12 hours of normal work. Perhaps needless to say that these numbers always reflect the runtime on the Windows platform, 
  since all the power-saving drivers are written for Windows. Because of my two-year-long relationship with OS X, I got really used 
  to the UNIX underpinnings, and the omni-presence of the command line. 
</p>

<p>
  Using Windows just <strong>doesn’t feel right</strong> anymore.
</p>

<p>
  So I had two options: I could hack my way around getting OS X to run, or go with Linux.
</p>

<p>
  The decision was pretty easy, since I knew that I can forget about the great battery life on OS X, because the drivers are 
  close to non-existent. Linux on the other hand has a much bigger community of hackers and tinkerers, and is known to work 
  rather well on netbooks.
</p>

<p>
  Okay, so Linux, what now?
</p>

<p>
  I had to pick a distribution, and since I’m kind of fond of Ubuntu and how they’re popularizing Linux 
  in the general public, I went for the Ubuntu Netbook Edition 10.04.
  The UNE boasts a customized interface to look better and at the same time conserve precious screen real estate on 
  the small netbook displays.
</p>

<p>
  Let’s look at an overview of the things I did, to get substantial power savings, performance gains and a totally minimalistic UI:
  </p>
<ul>
<li>System update</li>
    <li>Lighter applications</li>
    <li>Lighter window manager</li>
    <li>UI tweaks</li>
    <li>Power saving tweaks</li>      
  </ul>
<p>
  It has been an interesting journey and I’m happy to share it with you. The process involved many days of googling and trying out applications,
  to get the most minimalistic platform.
</p>

<p>
  Now I can say I am satisfied with the results and the platform I chose. I regained faith in desktop Linux, though it still has work to be done,
  to be able to match the feeling of using the Mac OS X.
</p>

