a.com/open-source/news/2010/03/ubuntu-dumps-the-brown-introduces-new-theme.ars">Ubuntu dumps the brown, introduces new theme and branding</a>”, noting how <a title="Ubuntu" href="http://ubuntu.com">Ubuntu</a> is refreshing and overhauling it’s UI and branding.</p>
<p>I don’t know if it’s just me, but I see a remarkable similarity with Mac OS X now with this top menu bar. Especially the icons for WiFi and Bluetooth are very alike. Switch the Apple with the Canonical logo at the far left and you got it.</p>
<p>Mac OS X Snow Leopard menu bar:</p>
<p><img height="15" width="640" alt="Mac OS X: Snow Leopard menu bar" src="http://i48.tinypic.com/dyxd1t.jpg"/></p>
<p>Ubuntu menu bar:</p>
<p><img height="15" width="640" alt="Ubuntu menu bar" src="http://i46.tinypic.com/2iqjxjm.jpg"/></p>
<p>I don’t mind this, though, and actually think it’s great, because good practices are to be imitated. Same as Windows 7 that adopted the Dock.app functionality of combining QuickLaunch with the taskbar.</p>
<p>I also would like to saj kudos to Canonical, for making one of their goals, to make the desktop Linux <b>beautiful</b>. I think that’s the key to success, as one of my major grudges towards Linux on the desktop is, that no matter all the advances in KDE and Gnome, I’m still not comfortable working with it. It lacks the necessary level of <i>polish</i> that I’m used to on a Mac.</p>
<p>But hey, they seem to be on a good way to a better place.</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:37:"http://breakthebit.org/post/426095326";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:37:"http://breakthebit.org/post/426095326";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Thu, 04 Mar 2010 12:44:00 +0100";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:6:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"ubuntu";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"macosx";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2:"ui";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"interface";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:7:"menubar";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:5;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"menu bar";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:17;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:1:{s:0:"";a:5:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:20:"Laptop battery myths";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:376:"<a href="http://www.marco.org/195827279">Laptop battery myths</a>: <p>This article puts it very clear, that most articles about battery life and conservation of batt